<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is semantic versioning?", answer: "Semantic versioning (SemVer) is a versioning scheme using three numbers: MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH. MAJOR increments for incompatible API changes, MINOR for backward-compatible new features, and PATCH for backward-compatible bug fixes. For example, going from 1.2.3 to 2.0.0 signals a breaking change, while 1.2.3 to 1.3.0 means new features were added without breaking existing functionality." },
  { question: "When should I bump the major version?", answer: "Bump the major version when you make incompatible changes to the public API. This signals to users that they may need to modify their code to work with the new version. Examples include removing or renaming public methods, changing function signatures, altering default behavior, or restructuring data formats. A major bump resets both minor and patch to zero." },
  { question: "When should I bump the minor version?", answer: "Bump the minor version when you add functionality in a backward-compatible manner. New features, new API endpoints, new optional parameters, and new configuration options all warrant a minor bump. Users can upgrade without changing their existing code. A minor bump resets the patch number to zero but does not affect the major version." },
  { question: "What are pre-release identifiers?", answer: "Pre-release identifiers are appended after the patch number with a hyphen, like 2.0.0-alpha.1 or 1.5.0-beta.3. They indicate that the version is unstable and may not satisfy the normal compatibility requirements. Pre-release versions have lower precedence than the associated normal version, so 1.0.0-alpha < 1.0.0. They are useful for testing before an official release." },
  { question: "What is build metadata in SemVer?", answer: "Build metadata is appended after the version with a plus sign, like 1.0.0+20240101 or 1.0.0-beta+build.123. Unlike pre-release identifiers, build metadata is ignored when determining version precedence. Two versions that differ only in build metadata are considered equal. Build metadata typically includes build numbers, commit hashes, or timestamps for traceability." }
]) %>

<%= calculator_schema_with_ratings(
  name: "Semantic Version Bump Calculator",
